-- ASX, BHP, GPT, Mirvac, Rio, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-10-12T22:05:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-12/asx-bhp-gpt-mirvac-newcrest-rio-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in  Australia . This preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index futures contract due in December
advanced 0.8 percent to 4,667 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The
Bank of New York Australia ADR Index slipped 1 percent. The
S&P/ASX 200 Index declined 1.7 percent to 4,618.20.  Mining shares: A measure of metals traded in London rose
0.9 percent yesterday.    BHP Billiton Ltd . (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, gained 1.7 percent to A$40.74 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts declined 1 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
slumped 2.8 percent to A$77.87 in Sydney.  Oil producers: Crude for November delivery fell 0.7 percent
to settle at $81.67 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.    Woodside Petroleum Ltd . (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, lost 2 percent to A$44.04.  Gold producers: Gold futures for December delivery fell 0.6
percent to settle at $1,346.70 at 1:48 p.m. in New York.    Newcrest Mining Ltd . (NCM AU), Australia’s largest gold
producer, fell 3 percent to A$40.88. St. Barbara Ltd. (SBM AU)
slipped 1.2 percent to 41 Australian cents.        ASX Ltd . (ASX AU): Australia will allow rival stock
exchanges to move into its market and break the monopoly of the
Australian Securities Exchange, the Australian Financial Review
reported, citing Assistant Treasurer Bill Shorten. ASX shares
slipped 0.9 percent to A$34.15.    GPT Group  (GPT AU): The Australian property trust had its
stock rating raised to “neutral” from “underweight” by
analysts at JPMorgan Chase & Co. The stock dropped 0.7 percent
to A$2.88.    Mirvac Group  (MGR AU): The Australian real-estate
investment trust had its stock rating raised to “neutral” from
“underweight” by analysts at JPMorgan Chase & Co. The shares
fell 1.5 percent to A$1.28    Straits Resources Ltd . (SRL AU): The Australian mining
company that sold coal and nickel assets in the past year said
it’s been approached to sell its remaining S$489 million ($374
million) share in an Indonesian coal miner. Straits Resources
shares were unchanged at A$1.85.  To contact the reporter for this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 